ght=300\n | xAxisTitle=Age group\n | yAxisTitle=Number of cases\n | legend=Series\n | type=stackedrect\n | x=0-9,10-19,20-29,30-39,40-49,50-59,60-69,70-100\n | y1=3,16,28,17,30,25,14,6\n | y2=\n | y1Title=Confirmed cases\n | y2Title= <!--gender?-->\n | colors=seagreen, orchid\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://epidemic-stats.com/coronavirus/faroe-islands epidemic-stats]\n\n* [https://visalist.io/emergency/coronavirus/faroe-islands-country visalist-coronavirus-faroeislands]\n\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in the Faroe Islands|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Danish dependencies|Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the Faroe Islands]]\n", "name_user": "Johndaviddeoliveira", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_Faroe_Islands"}
{"title_page": "The Princess Bride (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1987 film by Rob Reiner}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Princess Bride\n| image          = Princess bride.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Rob Reiner]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Andrew Scheinman]]\n* Rob Reiner\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[William Goldman]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[The Princess Bride (novel)|The Princess Bride]]''|William Goldman}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Cary Elwes]]\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]]\n* [[Chris Sarandon]]\n* [[Christopher Guest]]\n* [[Wallace Shawn]]\n* [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]]\n* [[Robin Wright]]\n* [[Peter Falk]]\n* [[Fred Savage]]\n* [[Billy Crystal]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Mark Knopfler]]\n| cinematography = [[Adrian Biddle]]\n| editing        = [[Robert Leighton (film editor)|Robert Leighton]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Act III Communications]]\n* Buttercup Films\n* The Princess Bride Ltd.\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[20th Century Fox]] {{Small|(North&nbsp;America)}}\n* [[Vestron Video|Interaccess Film Distribution]] {{Small|(International)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|1987|09|25}}<ref name=HR>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/princess-bride-cast-photos-then-and-now-1021697 | title = The Cast of 'The Princess Bride,' Then and Now | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181022113400/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/princess-bride-cast-photos-then-and-now-1021697 |archive-date=October 22, 2018 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] }}</ref>\n| runtime        = 98 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $16 million\n| gross          = $30.9 million\n}}\n\n'''''The Princess Bride''''' is a 1987 American [[fantasy]] [[adventure film|adventure]] [[comedy film]] directed and co-produced by [[Rob Reiner]], starring [[Cary Elwes]], [[Robin Wright]], [[Mandy Patinkin]], [[Chris Sarandon]], [[Wallace Shawn]], [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]], and [[Christopher Guest]]. Adapted by [[William Goldman]] from his 1973 novel ''[[The Princess Bride (novel)|The Princess Bride]]'', it tells the story of a farmhand named Westley, accompanied by companions befriended along the way, who must rescue his true love Princess Buttercup from the odious Prince Humperdinck. The film essentially preserves the novel's narrative style by presenting the story as a book being read by a grandfather ([[Peter Falk]]) to his sick grandson ([[Fred Savage]]).\n\nThe film was first released in the United States on September 25, 1987,<ref name=HR/> and was well-received by critics at the time, but was only a modest box office success. Over time the film has become a [[cult classic]].<ref name=\"our-time\"/> The film is number 50 on the [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]]'s \"100 Funniest Movies\", number 88 on The [[American Film Institute]]'s (AFI) \"[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Passions]]\" list of the 100 greatest film love stories, and 46 in [[Channel 4]]'s 50 Greatest Comedy Films list.<ref>{{cite web | title=50 Greatest Comedy Films | url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/50-greatest-comedy-films | date=January 27, 2010 | work=Channel4.com | publisher=Channel 4 | accessdate=October 30, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104165534/http://www.channel4.com/programmes/50-greatest-comedy-films | archive-date=November 4, 2011 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2016, the film was inducted into the [[National Film Registry]], being deemed as \"culturally, historically or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite web |date= December 14, 2016 |author= Camila Domonoske |title= 'Lion King,' 'Princess Bride,' 'The Birds' Among Additions To Film Registry |url= https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/12/14/505556002/lion-king-princess-bride-the-birds-among-additions-to-film-registry |website= NPR.org |accessdate= December 15, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171201131509/https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/12/14/505556002/lion-king-princess-bride-the-birds-among-additions-to-film-registry |archive-date= December 1, 2017 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe film is an enactment of a book read to a sick boy from [[Chicago]], who is initially dismissive of the story, by his grandfather, with occasional interruptions of the scenes in this [[frame story]].\n\nA beautiful young woman named Buttercup lives on a farm in the fictional country of Florin. Whenever she instructs the farmhand Westley, he complies and answers, \"As you wish.\" She eventually realizes that he truly means \"I love you\" and that she loves him in return. He leaves to seek his fortune so they can marry, but his ship is attacked by the [[Dread Pirate Roberts]], who is infamous for never leaving survivors, and Westley is believed dead.\n\nFive years later, Buttercup is forced into marriage to Prince Humperdinck, heir to the throne of Florin. Before the wedding, she is kidnapped by three outlaws: a short [[Sicilian people|Sicilian]] boss named Vizzini, a giant from [[Greenland]] named Fezzik, and a [[Spanish people|Spanish]] [[fencing]] master named [[Inigo Montoya]], who seeks revenge against a six-fingered man who killed his father. The outlaws are pursued separately by a masked man in black and Prince Humperdinck with a complement of soldiers.\n\nThe man in black catches up to the outlaws at the top of the Cliffs of Insanity. He defeats Inigo in a duel and knocks him unconscious, chokes Fezzik until he passes out, and kills Vizzini by tricking him into drinking from a cup containing poison. He takes Buttercup prisoner and they flee, stopping to rest at the edge of a gorge. When Buttercup correctly guesses that he is the Dread Pirate Roberts she becomes enraged at him for killing Westley. When Buttercup sees Humperdinck and his men appearing, she shoves Roberts down a hill and wishes death upon him. As he tumbles down, he shouts, \"As you wish!\" Realizing Roberts is Westley, she throws herself into the gorge after him and they are reunited. Westley explains the Dread Pirate Roberts is actually a title passed on by subsequent holders: he had taken the title so the previous Roberts could retire. They pass through the dangerous Fire Swamp, which is inhabited by rodents of unusual size (ROUS), but are captured as they leave by Humperdinck and his sadistic [[vizier]] Count Rugen, who is revealed to be Inigo's father's killer. Buttercup agrees to return with Humperdinck in exchange for Westley's release, but Humperdinck secretly orders Rugen to lock Westley in his torture chamber, the Pit of Despair.\n\nWhen Buttercup expresses unhappiness at marrying Humperdinck, he promises to search for Westley. However, his real plan is to start a war with the neighboring country of Guilder by killing Buttercup and framing Guilder for her death (he had hired Vizzini to kill her for that same purpose). Meanwhile, Inigo and Fezzik reunite when Humperdinck orders the thieves arrested in the nearby forest, and Fezzik tells Inigo about Rugen. Inigo decides that they need Westley's help to get into the castle. Buttercup berates Humperdinck after learning that he has not tried to find Westley; enraged, Humperdinck imprisons Buttercup in her chambers, and tortures Westley to death. Inigo and Fezzik follow the cries of anguish through the forest. They find Westley's body and bring him to a [[folk healer]], Miracle Max, whom Humperdinck has recently fired. He discovers that Westley is only \"mostly dead\" due to being sustained by his love for Buttercup, and revives him to a state of heavy paralysis.\n\nAfter Westley, Inigo and Fezzik invade the castle, Humperdinck panics and orders the wedding ceremony shortened. Inigo finds and kills Rugen in a duel, repeatedly taunting him with his greeting of vengeance: \"Hello, my name is Inigo Montoya. You killed my father. Prepare to die.\" Westley finds Buttercup, who is about to commit suicide, assuring her that the marriage is invalid because she never said \"I do\". Still partly paralyzed, he bluffs his way out of a duel with Humperdinck and they flee the castle. Westley rides away with Buttercup, Inigo and Fezzik before sharing a passionate kiss with Buttercup.\n\nBack in the boy's bedroom, the boy eagerly asks his grandfather to read the story to him again the next day, to which the grandfather replies, \"As you wish.\"\n\n==Cast==\n\n===Framing story===\n* [[Peter Falk]] as Grandpa/The Narrator\n* [[Fred Savage]] as The Grandson\n* [[Betsy Brantley]] as The Mother\n\n===Main story===\n* [[Cary Elwes]] as Westley/[[Dread Pirate Roberts]]/The Man in Black\n* [[Robin Wright]] as Buttercup/The Princess Bride\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]] as [[Inigo Montoya]]\n* [[Chris Sarandon]] as Prince Humperdinck\n* [[Christopher Guest]] as Count Tyrone Rugen\n* [[Wallace Shawn]] as Vizzini\n* [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]] as Fezzik\n* [[Billy Crystal]] as Miracle Max\n* [[Carol Kane]] as Valerie, Max's wife\n* [[Peter Cook]] as The Impressive Clergyman\n* [[Mel Smith]] as The Albino\n* [[Margery Mason]] as The Ancient Booer\n* [[Malcolm Storry]] as Yellin, a soldier of Florin\n* [[Willoughby Gray]] as The King\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nRob Reiner, who had been enamored with Goldman's book ever since he was given it as a gift from his father, [[Carl Reiner]], realized he wanted to make the film adaptation after successfully demonstrating his filmmaking skill with the release of ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]'' in 1984.<ref name=\"variety 30th\">{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2017/film/features/the-princess-bride-turns-30-1202565060/ | title = 'The Princess Bride' Turns 30: Rob Reiner, Robin Wright, Billy Crystal Dish About Making the Cult Classic | first = Susan | last = King | date = September 24, 2017 | accessdate = December 29, 2017 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171230114650/http://variety.com/2017/film/features/the-princess-bride-turns-30-1202565060/ | archive-date = December 30, 2017 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> During production of ''[[Stand by Me (film)|Stand by Me]]'', released in 1986, Reiner had spoken to an executive at [[Paramount Pictures]] regarding what his next film would be, and suggested the adaptation of ''The Princess Bride''. He was told they could not, leading Reiner to discover that several studios had previously attempted to bring Goldman's book to the big screen without success.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/>\n\nThose previous attempts included [[20th Century Fox]], which paid Goldman $500,000 for the film rights and to do a screenplay in 1973.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weiler|first1=A. H.|title=News of the Screen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/09/30/archives/news-of-the-screen-brolin-writes-new-prescription-westfall-ready.html|accessdate=April 17, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=September 30, 1973|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202153018/http://www.nytimes.com/1973/09/30/archives/news-of-the-screen-brolin-writes-new-prescription-westfall-ready.html|archive-date=December 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\"Schlesinger to Direct West Work.\" Haber, Joyce. ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] September 19, 1973: d12.</ref> [[Richard Lester]] was signed to direct and the movie was almost made, but the head of production at Fox was fired and the project was put on hiatus. Goldman subsequently bought back the film rights to the novel with his own money.<ref>Goldman, 2000 p 25-26</ref> Other directors had also attempted to adapt the book, including [[Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut]], [[Robert Redford]] and [[Norman Jewison]],<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/> and at one point, [[Christopher Reeve]] was interested in playing Westley in one planned adaption.<ref>William Goldman, ''The Big Picture?: Who Killed Hollywood and Other Essays'', Applause, 2000 p 189</ref> Reiner found success by gaining financial support from [[Norman Lear]], who Reiner knew from ''[[All in the Family]]'' and who had funded production of ''This is Spinal Tap'', with the production to be distributed by 20th Century Fox.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/><ref>Goldman, 2000 p 27</ref> Reiner worked closely with Goldman to adapt the book for the screenplay.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nReiner had quickly decided on Cary Elwes for Westley, based on his performance in ''[[Lady Jane (1986 film)|Lady Jane]]''; however, during the casting period in Los Angeles, Elwes was in Germany on set for ''[[Maschenka (1987 film)|Maschenka]]''. Reiner flew out to [[Munich]] to meet with Elwes, confirming his appropriateness for the role. While Reiner and casting director Jane Jenkins auditioned other actors for Westley, they knew Elwes was perfect for the part.<ref name=\"vice casting\">{{cite web | url = https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/xwg5xq/what-it-was-like-finding-the-legendary-cast-of-the-princess-bride | title = What It Was Like Finding the Legendary Cast of 'The Princess Bride' | first = Jennifer | last = Vineyard | date = September 29, 2017 | accessdate = December 29, 2017 | work = [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180204075910/https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/xwg5xq/what-it-was-like-finding-the-legendary-cast-of-the-princess-bride | archive-date = February 4, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Elwes had read the book in his childhood and associated himself with the character of Westley, but never believed he would have the opportunity to play him.<ref name=\"abc elwes 30th\">{{cite web | url = http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/princess-bride-turns-30-cary-elwes-shares-stories/story?id=49990697 | title = 'The Princess Bride' turns 30: Cary Elwes shares stories from the set | first = Leslie | last = Messer | date = September 25, 2017 | accessdate = December 29, 2017 | work = [[ABC News]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171230114733/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/princess-bride-turns-30-cary-elwes-shares-stories/story?id=49990697 | archive-date = December 30, 2017 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nRobin Wright was cast late in the process, about a week before filming; Reiner and Jenkins had auditioned a number of English actresses but had not found their ideal Buttercup.<ref name=\"abc elwes 30th\"/> Wright's agent had heard of the casting call and encouraged Wright to audition. Though initially shy, Wright impressed Jenkins, and later Reiner. They invited Wright to come meet Goldman at his house. Jenkins recalls: \"The doorbell rang. Rob went to the door, and literally, as he opened the door, [Wright] was standing there in this little white summer dress, with her long blonde hair, and she had a halo from the sun. She was backlit by God. And Bill Goldman looked across the room at her, and he said, 'Well, that's what I wrote.' It was the most perfect thing.\"<ref name=\"vice casting\"/>\n\nMandy Patinkin and Wallace Shawn were early choices for the cast; Shawn in particular was chosen as Vizzini due to his diminutive size to contrast that of the giant Fezzik.<ref name=\"vice casting\"/>\n\nWhen Goldman originally shopped his novel in the early 1970s, his first choice for Fezzik was Andre the Giant, whose wrestling schedule left him unavailable for filming. Goldman's second choice was [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], who at that time was almost unknown as an actor. However, by the time ''The Princess Bride'' was finally green-lit, Schwarzenegger was a major film star and the studio could not afford him. Jenkins contacted the [[World Wrestling Federation]] to ask about hiring Andre, but were told that the filming conflicted with a wrestling match in Tokyo that would pay him $5 million. Jenkins auditioned other tall men, including [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], [[Lou Ferrigno]] and [[Carel Struycken]], but these did not pan out. Near the end of casting, the World Wrestling Federation told Jenkins that Andre's match in Tokyo had been cancelled, clearing him to play the role of Fezzik.<ref name=\"vice casting\"/>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Cliffs of Moher, looking north.jpg|thumb|The [[establishing shot]] of the Cliffs of Insanity is the [[Cliffs of Moher]] in [[County Clare]], Ireland.]]\nThe film was shot in various locations in [[Great Britain]] and [[Ireland]] in late 1986:<ref>{{cite web|author=Kent Film Office|url=http://kentfilmoffice.co.uk/1987/03/the-princess-bride-1987/|title=Kent Film Office The Princess Bride Film Focus}}</ref>\n* [[Carl Wark]], Sheffield, England\n* [[Burnham Beeches]], Buckinghamshire, England\n* [[River Lathkill|Lathkill Dale]] where it meets Cales Dale (the 'Battle of wits' scene)\n* [[Cave Dale]], [[Castleton, Derbyshire|Castleton]], Derbyshire, England\n* Bradley Rocks and [[Robin Hood's Stride]], Birchover, Derbyshire, England\n* [[Cliffs of Moher]], [[County Clare]], Ireland (for the Cliffs of Insanity)\n* [[Haddon Hall]], [[Bakewell]], Derbyshire, England\n* [[Penshurst Place]], [[Kent]], England\n\nThe framing story scenes, the last to be filmed, were recorded at [[Shepperton Studios]] in [[Surrey]].<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/>\n\nReiner rented a house in England near these sites and frequently invited the cast over for meals and light-hearted get-togethers. Many cast members believed this helped to create a sense of \"family\" that helped to improve their performances for the film.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/><ref name=\"ew 30th\">{{cite web | url = https://ew.com/movies/2017/10/03/princess-bride-cary-elwes-30th-anniversary/ | title = Cary Elwes talks sword fights, Andr\u00e9 the Giant, and The Princess Bride | first = Devan | last = Coggan | date = October 3, 2017 | accessdate = December 29, 2017 | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171230114715/http://ew.com/movies/2017/10/03/princess-bride-cary-elwes-30th-anniversary/ | archive-date = December 30, 2017 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nCary Elwes and Mandy Patinkin learned to [[Fencing|fence]] (both left- and right-handed) for the film, and performed these scenes themselves, outside of the two somersaults, which were performed by stunt doubles.<ref>Reiner, Rob. ''The Princess Bride''. DVD audio commentary. Directed by Rob Reiner. 1987; Santa Monica, CA: MGM Home Entertainment, 2001. ''(see Ch. 06, time 17:45)''</ref> They were trained by fencing instructors [[Bob Anderson (fencer)|Bob Anderson]] and Peter Diamond, both of whom had also worked on training the actors in the original ''[[Star Wars]]'' trilogy. Elwes and Patinkin spent about three weeks prior to filming learning to fence, and spent most of their off-camera free time practicing.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/><ref name=\"ew 30th\"/> Anderson encouraged the two to learn the other's choreography for the fight to help them anticipate the movements and avoid an accident.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/> They also watched as many sword fights from previous films to see how they could improve on those.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/>\n\nPopular professional wrestler Andr\u00e9 the Giant had undergone major back surgery prior to filming and, despite his great size and strength, could not support the weight of Elwes during their fight scene or Wright for a scene at the end of the film. For the wrestling scene, when Elwes hangs on Andr\u00e9's back, he was actually walking on a series of ramps below the camera during close-ups. For the wide shots, a stunt double took the place of Andr\u00e9.<ref>Reiner, Rob. ''The Princess Bride''. DVD audio commentary. Directed by Rob Reiner. 1987; Santa Monica, CA: MGM Home Entertainment, 2001. ''(see Ch. 08, time 25:40)''</ref> When he was apparently carrying Wright, she was actually suspended by cables.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.contactmusic.com/robin-wright/news/wright-giant-was-in-so-much-pain-on-the-princess-bride-set_1134854 | title = Wright: 'Giant Was In So Much Pain On The Princess Bride Set' | date = March 10, 2010 | website = [[Contactmusic.com]] | access-date = October 20, 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160221030137/http://www.contactmusic.com/robin-wright/news/wright-giant-was-in-so-much-pain-on-the-princess-bride-set_1134854 | archive-date = February 21, 2016 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBilly Crystal and Carol Kane spent time before traveling to England to work out the backstory between Miracle Max and his wife, and develop a rapport for their characters. Once on set, Reiner allowed the pair to improvise some of their lines.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|The Princess Bride (soundtrack)}}\nThe original soundtrack album was composed by [[Mark Knopfler]] of [[Dire Straits]], and released by [[Warner Bros. Records]] in the United States and [[Vertigo Records]] internationally in November 1987. The album contains the song \"Storybook Love\", performed by [[Willy DeVille]] and produced by Mark Knopfler. It was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] at the [[60th Academy Awards]].<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|title=The Princess Bride|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-princess-bride-original-soundtrack-r84523|website=Allmusic|accessdate=November 23, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102074244/http://allmusic.com/album/the-princess-bride-original-soundtrack-r84523|archive-date=November 2, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn his audio commentary of the film on the special edition DVD, director [[Rob Reiner]] said that only Knopfler could create a soundtrack to capture the film's quirky yet romantic nature. Reiner was an admirer of Knopfler's work but did not know him before working on the film. He sent the script to him hoping he would agree to score the film. Knopfler agreed on one condition: that somewhere in the film Reiner would include the {{USS|Coral Sea|CV-43}} baseball cap (which had been modified to say \"USS Ooral Sea OV-4B\") he wore as Marty DiBergi in ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]''. Reiner was unable to produce the original cap, but did include a similar cap in the grandson's room. Knopfler later said he was joking.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nThe film was initially a modest success,<ref>{{cite journal | title= 'The Princess Bride' Turns 20 | journal = [[The Palm Beach Post]] | last = Gray Streeter |first = Leslie | date = December 9, 2007 | quote = [w]as a modest hit[...] }}</ref> grossing $30.8 million at the United States and Canada box office,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=princessbride.htm |title= The Princess Bride (1987 |work= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate= September 27, 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181104204409/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=princessbride.htm |archive-date= November 4, 2018 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref> on a $16 million production budget.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reiner's 'Princess' is charming|journal=[[USA Today]]|last=Clark|first=Mike|date=September 25, 1987|quote=Despite a $16 million budget, [...]}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''The Princess Bride'' received critical acclaim. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a 97% \"Certified Fresh\" rating, based on 74 reviews, with an average rating of 8.34/10. The site's consensus states: \"A delightfully postmodern fairy tale, ''The Princess Bride'' is a deft, intelligent mix of swashbuckling, romance, and comedy that takes an age-old damsel-in-distress story and makes it fresh.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = The Princess Bride (1987) | url = https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/princess_bride/ | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Flixster]] | accessdate =March 28, 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130830074446/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/princess_bride/ | archive-date = August 30, 2013 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds a score of 77 out of 100, based on 20 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = The Princess Bride | url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-princess-bride | publisher = [[CBS]] | work = [[Metacritic]] | access-date = November 14, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121025113832/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-princess-bride | archive-date = October 25, 2012 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all}}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade \"A+\" on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |url-status= live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= December 20, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[Gene Siskel]] and [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film a \"two thumbs up\" rating on [[At the Movies (1986 TV program)|their television program]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/atm/reviews.html?sec=1&subsec=1737 |title=''At the Movies with Gene Siskel and Roger Ebert'' review |publisher=Bventertainment.go.com |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070401175155/http://www.nypost.com/seven/02162007/entertainment/theater/bride_not_to_be_theater_michael_riedel.htm |archive-date= April 1, 2007 }}</ref> Ebert also wrote a very favorable print review in his column for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web | author = Roger Ebert | authorlink = Roger Ebert | url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19871009/REVIEWS/710090301/1023 | title = The Princess Bride | work = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date = October 9, 1987 | access-date = December 5, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121012155114/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F19871009%2FREVIEWS%2F710090301%2F1023 | archive-date = October 12, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Richard Corliss]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' said the film was fun for the whole family,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,965565,00.html | title = Errol Flynn Meets Gunga Din THE PRINCESS BRIDE | author = Richard Corliss | work = Time | date = September 21, 1987 | access-date = June 28, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930093032/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,965565,00.html | archive-date = September 30, 2007 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and later, ''Time'' listed the film as one of the \"Best of '87\".<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,966369,00.html | title = Best of '87 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012153630/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,966369,00.html |archive-date=October 12, 2007 | magazine = Time | date = January 4, 1988 }}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the cast and the sweetness of the film.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B0DE2D8133DF936A1575AC0A961948260 | title = New York Times review | author = Janet Maslin | date = September 25, 1987 | author-link = Janet Maslin | newspaper = The New York Times }}</ref>\n\n===Legacy===\n''The Princess Bride'' was not a major box-office success, but it became a cult classic after its release to the home video market. The film is widely regarded as eminently quotable.<ref name=\"our-time\">{{cite web |last=Clarke |first=Suzan | url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2011/10/princess-bride-reunion-thanks-to-entertainment-weekly-magazine/ | title= 'Princess Bride' Reunion, Thanks to Entertainment Weekly Magazine |publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=October 7, 2011 | accessdate=March 9, 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008023923/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2011/10/princess-bride-reunion-thanks-to-entertainment-weekly-magazine/ |archivedate=October 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"wizard2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/princess-bride-the|title=Reelviews Movie Reviews: The Princess Bride|date=January 4, 2002|accessdate=October 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209061003/http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/princess-bride-the|archive-date=December 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Elwes noted in 2017, on the film's 30th anniversary, that fans still frequently come up to him and quote lines from the movie. According to him Wallace Shawn had it \"worse\", in that any time Wallace made a small error like dropping his keys, people would shout \"Inconceivable!\" to him.<ref name=\"ew 30th\"/>\n\nIn 2000, readers of ''[[Total Film]]'' magazine voted ''The Princess Bride'' the 38th greatest comedy film of all time. In 2006, William Goldman's screenplay was selected by the [[Writers Guild of America]] as the 84th best screenplay of all time; it earned the same ranking in the Guild's 2013 update.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 | last= Savage | first = Sophia |date= February 27, 2013  |title= WGA Lists Greatest Screenplays, From 'Casablanca' and 'Godfather' to 'Memento' and 'Notorious' |publisher=Writers Guild of America, West |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130306065813/http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |archive-date=March 6, 2013}}</ref> The film was selected number 88 on The [[American Film Institute]]'s (AFI) \"[[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Passions]]\" listing the 100 greatest film love stories of all time. [[BBC Radio 5 Live|BBC Radio 5]]'s resident film critic, [[Mark Kermode]], is a fan of the film, frequently considering it a model to which similar films aspire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://duncmcrae.blogspot.com/2015/06/20-princess-bride.html|title=20: The Princess Bride|website=This AKTing Lark|date=June 27, 2015|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, a bar themed after the film, named \"As You Wish,\" opened in Chicago. The menu features 16 themed cocktails.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/princess-bride-themed-as-you-wish-bar-chicago/index.html|title=Inconceivable! A Princess Bride-themed bar is popping up in Chicago|first=Kristen |last=Rogers|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n;[[American Film Institute]] lists\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs500.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs Nominees |access-date=June 30, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220152415/http://afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs500.pdf |archive-date=December 20, 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Passions]] \u2013 No. 88\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes]]:\n** \"Hello. My name is Inigo Montoya. You killed my father; prepare to die!\" \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/quotes400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes Nominees |access-date=June 30, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628043426/http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/quotes400.pdf |archive-date=June 28, 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n* [[AFI's 10 Top 10]] \u2013 Nominated Fantasy Film<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/drop/ballot.pdf|title=AFI.com Error|work=afi.com|access-date=June 30, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911161721/http://www.afi.com/drop/ballot.pdf|archive-date=September 11, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, director [[Jason Reitman]] staged a [[Live Read|live dramatic reading]] of ''The Princess Bride'' script at the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] (LACMA), with [[Paul Rudd]] as Westley; [[Mindy Kaling]] as Buttercup; [[Patton Oswalt]] as Vizzini; [[Kevin Pollak]] as Miracle Max; [[Goran Visnjic]] as Inigo Montoya; [[Cary Elwes]] (switching roles) as Humperdinck; director [[Rob Reiner]] as the grandfather; and [[Fred Savage]] reprising his role as the grandson.<ref>{{cite news |date= December 30, 2011 |last= Breznican |first= Anthony |title= 'The Princess Bride' Comes Alive! |url= https://ew.com/article/2011/12/30/princess-bride-comes-alive/ |newspaper= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120115050153/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20558503,00.html|archive-date= January 15, 2012|url-status= live|df= mdy-all|accessdate= August 25, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, director [[Ari Folman]] released a [[live-action animated film]] titled ''[[The Congress (2013 film)|The Congress]]'', which directly referenced ''The Princess Bride''. Folman's film starred [[Robin Wright]], playing both a live and animated version of herself, as a [[Motion capture|digitally cloned]] actress.<ref>{{cite web |author=Manohla Dargis |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/05/movies/robin-wright-stars-in-the-congress.html |title=Movie Review\u2014A Princess Bride in a Digital Forever |quote=...Ms. Wright [plays] a version of herself \u2014 a midcareer actress named Robin Wright who...starred in \u201cThe Princess Bride\"... |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 4, 2014 |accessdate=December 27, 2018 |author-link=Manohla Dargis }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Cary Elwes wrote ''As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales From the Making of The Princess Bride,'' a behind-the-scenes account of the film's production, co-written with Joe Layden.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/movie-won-internet|title=The Movie That Won the Internet |last=Kelly |first=Caitlin|date=October 25, 2014 |work=The New Yorker|access-date=December 29, 2017 |issn=0028-792X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230114837/https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/movie-won-internet|archive-date=December 30, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> To help Elwes recall the production, Lear sent him a bound copy of the filming's [[call sheet]]s.<ref name=\"ew 30th\"/> The book debuted at #3 on the New York Times Bestseller list.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2014/11/02/hardcover-nonfiction/|title=New York Times Bestsellers List - Hardcover Nonfiction|access-date=October 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028114038/https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2014/11/02/hardcover-nonfiction/|archive-date=October 28, 2017|url-status=live|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cary-elwes.org/about|title=Cary Elwes: Biography|access-date=October 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028094209/https://www.cary-elwes.org/about|archive-date=October 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to a foreword by director Rob Reiner and a limited edition poster, the book includes exclusive photos and interviews with the cast members from the 25th anniversary cast reunion, as well as unique stories and set secrets from the making of the film.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/As-You-Wish/Cary-Elwes/9781476764023|title=As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales from the Making of The Princess Bride|work=Simon & Schuster|access-date=October 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028093640/http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/As-You-Wish/Cary-Elwes/9781476764023|archive-date=October 28, 2017|url-status=live|isbn=9781476764023|date=October 14, 2014|last1=Elwes|first1=Cary|last2=Layden|first2=Joe}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Savage reprised his role as The Grandson in a PG-13 version of ''[[Deadpool 2]]'' entitled ''Once Upon a Deadpool'', with [[Deadpool]] taking the role of The Narrator and reading the ''Deadpool 2''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s story to him at bedtime and skipping over the more adult parts from the R-rated version.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://collider.com/new-deadpool-movie-release-date|title=New 'Deadpool' Movie Coming This December; Will Feature 'Princess Bride' Star Fred Savage|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=September 28, 2018|accessdate=September 30, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929004447/http://collider.com/new-deadpool-movie-release-date/|archivedate=September 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"OnceUpon\">{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2018/11/deadpool-ryan-reynolds-disney-pg13-marvel-1202495981/ | title = 'Once Upon A Deadpool': Ryan Reynolds (and Fred Savage) On Franchise's PG-13 Plunge | first = Geoff | last = Boucher | date = November 5, 2018 | accessdate = November 5, 2018 | work = [[Deadline Hollywood]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181105223630/https://deadline.com/2018/11/deadpool-ryan-reynolds-disney-pg13-marvel-1202495981/ | archive-date = November 5, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Post-theatrical release==\n{{Anchor|DVD|Video|Home video history}} \nIn North America, the film was released on VHS and [[Laserdisc]] in 1988 by [[Nelson Entertainment]], the latter being a \"bare bones\" release in [[Matte (filmmaking)|unmatted full screen]]. [[New Line Home Video]] reissued the VHS in 1994.<ref>''Billboard'' (May 21, 1994), page 55.)</ref> The film was also released on [[Video CD]] by [[Philips]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=|first= |title=CD Films/Music|magazine=[[Sega Saturn Magazine]] |issue=13|publisher=[[Emap International Limited]]|date=November 1996|page=97}}</ref>\n\n[[The Criterion Collection]] released a matted widescreen version, bare bones version on laserdisc in 1989, supplementing it with [[liner notes]]. In 1997 Criterion re-released the Laserdisc as a \"[[special edition]]\". This edition was [[widescreen]] and included an [[audio commentary]] by Rob Reiner, William Goldman, Andrew Scheinman, Billy Crystal and Peter Falk (this commentary would also later appear on the Criterion Blu-ray and DVD release); excerpts from the novel read by Rob Reiner; behind the scenes footage; a production scrapbook by unit photographer Clive Coote; design sketches by production designer Norman Garwood; and excerpts from the television series ''Morton and Hayes'', directed by Christopher Guest.\n\nBy 2000, [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]] had acquired the US home video rights to the film (as part of the \"pre-1996 Polygram film library\" package) and released the film on VHS and DVD. The DVD release featured the soundtrack remastered in [[Dolby Digital|Dolby Digital 5.1]] with the film in wide and full screen versions, and included the original US [[theatrical trailer]]. The next year MGM re-released the film in another widescreen \"special edition\", this time with two audio commentaries\u2014one by Rob Reiner, the other by William Goldman\u2014\"As You Wish\", \"Promotional\", and \"Making Of\" [[featurette]]s;{{Clarify|date=December 2010}} a \"Cary Elwes Video Diary\"; the US and UK theatrical trailers; four television spots; a photo gallery; and a collectible booklet.\n\nIn 2006, MGM and [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]] released a two-disc set with varying covers\u2014the \"Dread Pirate\" and \"Buttercup\" editions. Each featured their respective character, but had identical features: in addition to the features in the previous release were, the \"Dread Pirate Roberts: Greatest Legend of the Seven Seas\", \"Love is Like a Storybook Story\", and \"Miraculous Make Up\" featurettes, \"The Quotable Battle of Wits\" game, and Fezzik's \"Guide to Florin\" booklet.\n\nAnother year later, to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the film, MGM and [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] (whose corporate parent [[The Walt Disney Company]] holds all US rights to the film except for US home video rights) released the film with flippable cover art featuring the title displayed in an [[ambigram]]. This DVD did not include any of the bonus features from the older editions, but had new short featurettes and a new game. A [[Blu-ray|Blu-ray Disc]] was released on March 17, 2009, encoded in 5.1 [[DTS-HD Master Audio]]. Special features include two audio commentaries, the original theatrical trailer and eight featurettes.<ref>{{cite press release | url = http://www.hometheaterforum.com/htf/ht-software-high-definition/282196-mgm-press-release-princess-bride-blu-ray.html | title = MGM Press Release: The Princess Bride (Blu-ray)] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090210180244/http://www.hometheaterforum.com/htf/ht-software-high-definition/282196-mgm-press-release-princess-bride-blu-ray.html |archive-date= February 10, 2009 | via = Home Theater Forum }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the film was released for download in the [[iTunes Store]].<ref name=\"https://itunes.apple.com/ca/movie/the-princess-bride/id263952053\">{{cite web | url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/movie/the-princess-bride/id263952053 | title=Itunes \u2013 Princess Bride | accessdate=October 31, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130626173718/https://itunes.apple.com/ca/movie/the-princess-bride/id263952053 | archive-date=June 26, 2013 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe film is also available in [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]] where it is published by [[Lions Gate Entertainment]]. Its extras are the theatrical trailer and text filmographies.\n\nThe Criterion Collection released the film on Blu-ray and DVD on October 30, 2018. It included a new 4K digital transfer, the same audio commentary from the Criterion LaserDisc release, an edited 1987 audiobook reading of Goldman's novel by director Rob Reiner, new programs on William Goldman's screenplay and tapestry, a new interview with art director Richard Holland, an essay by author [[Sloane Crosley]], and a Blu-ray exclusive book highlighting four screenplays, as well as Goldman's introduction to the 1995 screenplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=23637|title=Criterion Announces October Titles|date=July 16, 2018|accessdate=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717070802/http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=23637|archive-date=July 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nIt was announced that composer [[Adam Guettel]] was working with William Goldman on a musical adaptation of ''The Princess Bride'' in 2006. The project was abandoned in February 2007 after Goldman reportedly demanded 75 percent of the author's share, even though Guettel was writing both the music and the lyrics.<ref>{{cite news|last=Riedel |first=Michael |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/02162007/entertainment/theater/bride_not_to_be_theater_michael_riedel.htm |title='Bride' Not to Be While Broderick Balks at 'Producers' |work=New York Post |date=February 16, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070225201851/http://www.nypost.com/seven/02162007/entertainment/theater/bride_not_to_be_theater_michael_riedel.htm |archive-date=February 25, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn late 2013, [[Disney Theatrical Productions]] announced that they would adapt a stage musical adaptation of ''The Princess Bride''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/172985/inconceivable-disney-stage-adaptation-of-the-princess-bride-in-the-works/|title=Inconceivable! Disney Stage Adaptation of The Princess Bride in the Works|website=Broadway.com|last=Champion|first=Lindsay|date=November 11, 2013|accessdate=February 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164557/https://www.broadway.com/buzz/172985/inconceivable-disney-stage-adaptation-of-the-princess-bride-in-the-works/|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A website was launched a couple of months later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Disney-Launches-THE-PRINCESS-BRIDE-Musical-Website-20140208|title=Disney Launches THE PRINCESS BRIDE Stage Musical Website|website=Broadway World|last=Cerasaro|first=Pat|date=February 8, 2014|accessdate=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819114918/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Disney-Launches-THE-PRINCESS-BRIDE-Musical-Website-20140208|archive-date=August 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, Rob Reiner said the project was still in development despite \"roadblocks\" and that [[Marc Shaiman]], [[Randy Newman]] and [[John Mayer]] had all been approached to write songs, but had turned them down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/rob-reiner-says-he-still-wants-to-see-a-princess-bride-stage-musical-com-326627|title=Rob Reiner Says He Still Wants to See a Princess Bride Stage Musical|website=Playbill|last1=Viagas|first1=Robert|last2=Hetrick|first2=Adam|date=May 11, 2016|accessdate=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301224957/http://www.playbill.com/article/rob-reiner-says-he-still-wants-to-see-a-princess-bride-stage-musical-com-326627|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, ''The Princess Bride'' was adapted by players of a [[virtual reality]] social game, ''[[Rec Room (video game)|Rec Room]]'', into what is likely to be the world's first full-length virtual reality stage production. The duration of the production was approximately 80 minutes, and ran for a total of four shows.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carson |first1=Erin |title=The Princess Bride performed live -- in a VR app |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-princess-bride-gets-the-vr-treatment/ |quote= The Orange Bucket Acting Troupe...pulled off what's likely the first full-length play performed in VR. |website=[[CNET]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite AV Media |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Seev70WSSk |title=Orange Bucket Acting Troupe presents: The Princess Bride - A Rec Room Tale |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=October 31, 2018 |accessdate=March 11, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, PlayRoom Entertainment released ''The Princess Bride: Storming the Castle'', a board game based on the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/35524|title=The Princess Bride: Storming the Castle - Board Game - BoardGameGeek|work=boardgamegeek.com|access-date=August 18, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081108052204/http://www.boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/35524|archive-date=November 8, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''The Princess Bride Game'' is a [[casual game|casual video game]] developed and published by New York game development studio Worldwide Biggies.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/6180318.html?sid=6180318&action=convert | title = Princess Bride game conceivable | author = Sinclair, Brenden | website = [[GameSpot]] | date = October 3, 2007 | accessdate = June 3, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110525174538/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6180318.html?sid=6180318&action=convert | archive-date = May 25, 2011 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.joystiq.com/2007/10/03/as-you-wish-princess-bride-game-in-development/ | title = As you wish, Princess Bride game in development | author = McElroy, Justin | publisher = [[Joystiq]] | date = October 3, 2007 | accessdate = June 5, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150128143748/http://www.joystiq.com/2007/10/03/as-you-wish-princess-bride-game-in-development/ | archive-date = January 28, 2015 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Potential remake==\nIn a September 2019 biographical article on Norman Lear in ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] [[CEO]] [[Tony Vinciquerra]], speaking of Lear's works and interest in remaking them, stated \"Very famous people whose names I won\u2019t use, but they want to redo ''The Princess Bride.''\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/norman-lear-sony-deal-emmys-one-day-at-a-time-1203337598/ | title = Norman Lear Won't Stop: TV Legend's Sony Deal Renewal Takes Him to Age 100 | first = Michael | last = Schneider | date = September 17, 2019 | accessdate = September 17, 2019 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] }}</ref> The reaction to this via social media was very negative, with fans of the film asserting that a remake would be a bad idea and, in reference to the film, \"inconceivable\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/18/entertainment/the-princess-bride-remake-trnd/index.html | title = 'The Princess Bride' remake idea has people crying inconceivable | first =  Marianne | last = Garvey |date = September 18, 2019 | accessdate = September 18, 2019 | publisher = [[CNN]] }}</ref> Elwes paraphrased the film saying \"There\u2019s a shortage of perfect movies in this world. It would be a pity to damage this one.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user= Cary_Elwes |author-link= Cary Elwes |number= 1174124906327330816 |date= September 17, 2019 |title= There\u2019s a shortage of perfect movies in this world. It would be a pity to damage this one. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190920130745/https:/twitter.com/Cary_Elwes/status/1174124906327330816 |archive-date= September 20, 2019 |url-status= live}}</ref> [[Jamie Lee Curtis]], Guest's wife, stated \"there is only ONE ''The Princess Bride'' and it's William Goldman and [Reiner]'s\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/18/the-princess-bride-remake-rumors-spur-social-media-outrage.html | title = 'The Princess Bride' remake rumors spur social media outrage | first =  Sarah | last = Whitten |date = September 18, 2019 | accessdate = September 18, 2019 | publisher = [[CNBC]] }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Notelist-lr}}\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* Goldman, William, ''Which Lie Did They Tell?'', Bloomsbury, 2000\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last=Elwes |first=Cary |author-link1=Cary Elwes |last2=Layden |first2=Joe |date=2014 |title=As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales from the Making of The Princess Bride |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nNW5BAAAQBAJ |location=New York |publisher=Touchstone |oclc=878812649 |isbn=9781476764023}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.princessbrideforever.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|0093779}}\n* {{Tcmdb title|87152}}\n* {{Amg title|39218}}\n* {{AFI film|57788}}\n* {{mojo title|princessbride}}\n* [https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/6005-the-princess-bride-let-me-sum-up ''The Princess Bride: Let Me Sum Up''] an essay by [[Sloane Crosley]] at the [[Criterion Collection]]\n\n{{Rob Reiner}}\n{{William Goldman}}\n{{Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation 1981\u20132002}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Fantasy Film 1973\u20131990}}\n{{TIFF People's Choice Award}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States|1980s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Princess Bride, The}}\n[[Category:The Princess Bride| ]]\n[[Category:1980s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:1980s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:1980s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:1980s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1980s satirical films]]\n[[Category:1987 films]]\n[[Category:1980s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:1987 soundtracks]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:American children's adventure films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about royalty]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about weddings]]\n[[Category:Films based on adventure novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on romance novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by William Goldman]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Rob Reiner]]\n[[Category:Films set in a fictional country]]\n[[Category:Films about giants]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation winning works]]\n[[Category:Pirate films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by William Goldman]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1987 film by Rob Reiner}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Princess Bride\n| image          = Princess bride.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Rob Reiner]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Andrew Scheinman]]\n* Rob Reiner\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[William Goldman]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[The Princess Bride (novel)|The Princess Bride]]''|William Goldman}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Cary Elwes]]\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]]\n* [[Chris Sarandon]]\n* [[Christopher Guest]]\n* [[Wallace Shawn]]\n* [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]]\n* [[Robin Wright]]\n* [[Peter Falk]]\n* [[Fred Savage]]\n* [[Billy Crystal]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Mark Knopfler]]\n| cinematography = [[Adrian Biddle]]\n| editing        = [[Robert Leighton (film editor)|Robert Leighton]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Act III Communications]]\n* Buttercup Films\n* The Princess Bride Ltd.\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[20th Century Fox]] {{Small|(North&nbsp;America)}}\n* [[Vestron Video|Interaccess Film Distribution]] {{Small|(International)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|1987|09|25}}<ref name=HR>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/princess-bride-cast-photos-then-and-now-1021697 | title = The Cast of 'The Princess Bride,' Then and Now | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181022113400/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/princess-bride-cast-photos-then-and-now-1021697 |archive-date=October 22, 2018 | work = [[Hollywood Reporter]] }}</ref>\n| runtime        = 98 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $16 million\n| gross          = $30.9 million\n}}\n\n'''''The Princess Bride''''' is a 1987 American [[fantasy]] [[adventure film|adventure]] [[comedy film]] directed and co-produced by [[Rob Reiner]], starring [[Cary Elwes]], [[Robin Wright]], [[Mandy Patinkin]], [[Chris Sarandon]], [[Wallace Shawn]], [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]], and [[Christopher Guest]]. Adapted by [[William Goldman]] from his 1973 novel ''[[The Princess Bride (novel)|The Princess Bride]]'', it tells the story of a farmhand named Westley, accompanied by companions befriended along the way, who must rescue his true love Princess Buttercup from the odious Prince Humperdinck. The film essentially preserves the novel's narrative style by presenting the story as a book being read by a grandfather ([[Peter Falk]]) to his sick grandson ([[Fred Savage]]).\n\nThe film was first released in the United States on September 25, 1987,<ref name=HR/> and was well-received by critics at the time, but was only a modest box office success. Over time the film has become a [[cult classic]].<ref name=\"our-time\"/> The film is number 50 on the [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]]'s \"100 Funniest Movies\", number 88 on The [[American Film Institute]]'s (AFI) \"[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Passions]]\" list of the 100 greatest film love stories, and 46 in [[Channel 4]]'s 50 Greatest Comedy Films list.<ref>{{cite web | title=50 Greatest Comedy Films | url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/50-greatest-comedy-films | date=January 27, 2010 | work=Channel4.com | publisher=Channel 4 | accessdate=October 30, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104165534/http://www.channel4.com/programmes/50-greatest-comedy-films | archive-date=November 4, 2011 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2016, the film was inducted into the [[National Film Registry]], being deemed as \"culturally, historically or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite web |date= December 14, 2016 |author= Camila Domonoske |title= 'Lion King,' 'Princess Bride,' 'The Birds' Among Additions To Film Registry |url= https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/12/14/505556002/lion-king-princess-bride-the-birds-among-additions-to-film-registry |website= NPR.org |accessdate= December 15, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171201131509/https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/12/14/505556002/lion-king-princess-bride-the-birds-among-additions-to-film-registry |archive-date= December 1, 2017 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe film is an enactment of a book read to a sick boy from [[Chicago]], who is initially dismissive of the story, by his grandfather, with occasional interruptions of the scenes in this [[frame story]].\n\nA beautiful young woman named Buttercup lives on a farm in the fictional country of Florin. Whenever she instructs the farmhand Westley, he complies and answers, \"As you wish.\" She eventually realizes that he truly means \"I love you\" and that she loves him in return. He leaves to seek his fortune so they can marry, but his ship is attacked by the [[Dread Pirate Roberts]], who is infamous for never leaving survivors, and Westley is believed dead.\n\nFive years later, Buttercup is forced into marriage to Prince Humperdinck, heir to the throne of Florin. Before the wedding, she is kidnapped by three outlaws: a short [[Sicilian people|Sicilian]] boss named Vizzini, a giant from [[Greenland]] named Fezzik, and a [[Spanish people|Spanish]] [[fencing]] master named [[Inigo Montoya]], who seeks revenge against a six-fingered man who killed his father. The outlaws are pursued separately by a masked man in black and Prince Humperdinck with a complement of soldiers.\n\nThe man in black catches up to the outlaws at the top of the Cliffs of Insanity. He defeats Inigo in a duel and knocks him unconscious, chokes Fezzik until he passes out, and kills Vizzini by tricking him into drinking from a cup containing poison. He takes Buttercup prisoner and they flee, stopping to rest at the edge of a gorge. When Buttercup correctly guesses that he is the Dread Pirate Roberts she becomes enraged at him for killing Westley. When Buttercup sees Humperdinck and his men appearing, she shoves Roberts down a hill and wishes death upon him. As he tumbles down, he shouts, \"As you wish!\" Realizing Roberts is Westley, she throws herself into the gorge after him and they are reunited. Westley explains the Dread Pirate Roberts is actually a title passed on by subsequent holders: he had taken the title so the previous Roberts could retire. They pass through the dangerous Fire Swamp, which is inhabited by rodents of unusual size (ROUS), but are captured as they leave by Humperdinck and his sadistic [[vizier]] Count Rugen, who is revealed to be Inigo's father's killer. Buttercup agrees to return with Humperdinck in exchange for Westley's release, but Humperdinck secretly orders Rugen to lock Westley in his torture chamber, the Pit of Despair.\n\nWhen Buttercup expresses unhappiness at marrying Humperdinck, he promises to search for Westley. However, his real plan is to start a war with the neighboring country of Guilder by killing Buttercup and framing Guilder for her death (he had hired Vizzini to kill her for that same purpose). Meanwhile, Inigo and Fezzik reunite when Humperdinck orders the thieves arrested in the nearby forest, and Fezzik tells Inigo about Rugen. Inigo decides that they need Westley's help to get into the castle. Buttercup berates Humperdinck after learning that he has not tried to find Westley; enraged, Humperdinck imprisons Buttercup in her chambers, and tortures Westley to death. Inigo and Fezzik follow the cries of anguish through the forest. They find Westley's body and bring him to a [[folk healer]], Miracle Max, whom Humperdinck has recently fired. He discovers that Westley is only \"mostly dead\" due to being sustained by his love for Buttercup, and revives him to a state of heavy paralysis.\n\nAfter Westley, Inigo and Fezzik invade the castle, Humperdinck panics and orders the wedding ceremony shortened. Inigo finds and kills Rugen in a duel, repeatedly taunting him with his greeting of vengeance: \"Hello, my name is Inigo Montoya. You killed my father. Prepare to die.\" Westley finds Buttercup, who is about to commit suicide, assuring her that the marriage is invalid because she never said \"I do\". Still partly paralyzed, he bluffs his way out of a duel with Humperdinck and they flee the castle. Westley rides away with Buttercup, Inigo and Fezzik before sharing a passionate kiss with Buttercup.\n\nBack in the boy's bedroom, the boy eagerly asks his grandfather to read the story to him again the next day, to which the grandfather replies, \"As you wish.\"\n\n==Cast==\n\n===Framing story===\n* [[Peter Falk]] as Grandpa/The Narrator\n* [[Fred Savage]] as The Grandson\n* [[Betsy Brantley]] as The Mother\n\n===Main story===\n* [[Cary Elwes]] as Westley/[[Dread Pirate Roberts]]/The Man in Black\n* [[Robin Wright]] as Buttercup/The Princess Bride\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]] as [[Inigo Montoya]]\n* [[Chris Sarandon]] as Prince Humperdinck\n* [[Christopher Guest]] as Count Tyrone Rugen\n* [[Wallace Shawn]] as Vizzini\n* [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]] as Fezzik\n* [[Billy Crystal]] as Miracle Max\n* [[Carol Kane]] as Valerie, Max's wife\n* [[Peter Cook]] as The Impressive Clergyman\n* [[Mel Smith]] as The Albino\n* [[Margery Mason]] as The Ancient Booer\n* [[Malcolm Storry]] as Yellin, a soldier of Florin\n* [[Willoughby Gray]] as The King\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nRob Reiner, who had been enamored with Goldman's book ever since he was given it as a gift from his father, [[Carl Reiner]], realized he wanted to make the film adaptation after successfully demonstrating his filmmaking skill with the release of ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]'' in 1984.<ref name=\"variety 30th\">{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2017/film/features/the-princess-bride-turns-30-1202565060/ | title = 'The Princess Bride' Turns 30: Rob Reiner, Robin Wright, Billy Crystal Dish About Making the Cult Classic | first = Susan | last = King | date = September 24, 2017 | accessdate = December 29, 2017 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171230114650/http://variety.com/2017/film/features/the-princess-bride-turns-30-1202565060/ | archive-date = December 30, 2017 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> During production of ''[[Stand by Me (film)|Stand by Me]]'', released in 1986, Reiner had spoken to an executive at [[Paramount Pictures]] regarding what his next film would be, and suggested the adaptation of ''The Princess Bride''. He was told they could not, leading Reiner to discover that several studios had previously attempted to bring Goldman's book to the big screen without success.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/>\n\nThose previous attempts included [[20th Century Fox]], which paid Goldman $500,000 for the film rights and to do a screenplay in 1973.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weiler|first1=A. H.|title=News of the Screen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/09/30/archives/news-of-the-screen-brolin-writes-new-prescription-westfall-ready.html|accessdate=April 17, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=September 30, 1973|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202153018/http://www.nytimes.com/1973/09/30/archives/news-of-the-screen-brolin-writes-new-prescription-westfall-ready.html|archive-date=December 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\"Schlesinger to Direct West Work.\" Haber, Joyce. ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] September 19, 1973: d12.</ref> [[Richard Lester]] was signed to direct and the movie was almost made, but the head of production at Fox was fired and the project was put on hiatus. Goldman subsequently bought back the film rights to the novel with his own money.<ref>Goldman, 2000 p 25-26</ref> Other directors had also attempted to adapt the book, including [[Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut]], [[Robert Redford]] and [[Norman Jewison]],<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/> and at one point, [[Christopher Reeve]] was interested in playing Westley in one planned adaption.<ref>William Goldman, ''The Big Picture?: Who Killed Hollywood and Other Essays'', Applause, 2000 p 189</ref> Reiner found success by gaining financial support from [[Norman Lear]], who Reiner knew from ''[[All in the Family]]'' and who had funded production of ''This is Spinal Tap'', with the production to be distributed by 20th Century Fox.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/><ref>Goldman, 2000 p 27</ref> Reiner worked closely with Goldman to adapt the book for the screenplay.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nReiner had quickly decided on Cary Elwes for Westley, based on his performance in ''[[Lady Jane (1986 film)|Lady Jane]]''; however, during the casting period in Los Angeles, Elwes was in Germany on set for ''[[Maschenka (1987 film)|Maschenka]]''. Reiner flew out to [[Munich]] to meet with Elwes, confirming his appropriateness for the role. While Reiner and casting director Jane Jenkins auditioned other actors for Westley, they knew Elwes was perfect for the part.<ref name=\"vice casting\">{{cite web | url = https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/xwg5xq/what-it-was-like-finding-the-legendary-cast-of-the-princess-bride | title = What It Was Like Finding the Legendary Cast of 'The Princess Bride' | first = Jennifer | last = Vineyard | date = September 29, 2017 | accessdate = December 29, 2017 | work = [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180204075910/https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/xwg5xq/what-it-was-like-finding-the-legendary-cast-of-the-princess-bride | archive-date = February 4, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Elwes had read the book in his childhood and associated himself with the character of Westley, but never believed he would have the opportunity to play him.<ref name=\"abc elwes 30th\">{{cite web | url = http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/princess-bride-turns-30-cary-elwes-shares-stories/story?id=49990697 | title = 'The Princess Bride' turns 30: Cary Elwes shares stories from the set | first = Leslie | last = Messer | date = September 25, 2017 | accessdate = December 29, 2017 | work = [[ABC News]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171230114733/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/princess-bride-turns-30-cary-elwes-shares-stories/story?id=49990697 | archive-date = December 30, 2017 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nRobin Wright was cast late in the process, about a week before filming; Reiner and Jenkins had auditioned a number of English actresses but had not found their ideal Buttercup.<ref name=\"abc elwes 30th\"/> Wright's agent had heard of the casting call and encouraged Wright to audition. Though initially shy, Wright impressed Jenkins, and later Reiner. They invited Wright to come meet Goldman at his house. Jenkins recalls: \"The doorbell rang. Rob went to the door, and literally, as he opened the door, [Wright] was standing there in this little white summer dress, with her long blonde hair, and she had a halo from the sun. She was backlit by God. And Bill Goldman looked across the room at her, and he said, 'Well, that's what I wrote.' It was the most perfect thing.\"<ref name=\"vice casting\"/>\n\nMandy Patinkin and Wallace Shawn were early choices for the cast; Shawn in particular was chosen as Vizzini due to his diminutive size to contrast that of the giant Fezzik.<ref name=\"vice casting\"/>\n\nWhen Goldman originally shopped his novel in the early 1970s, his first choice for Fezzik was Andre the Giant, whose wrestling schedule left him unavailable for filming. Goldman's second choice was [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], who at that time was almost unknown as an actor. However, by the time ''The Princess Bride'' was finally green-lit, Schwarzenegger was a major film star and the studio could not afford him. Jenkins contacted the [[World Wrestling Federation]] to ask about hiring Andre, but were told that the filming conflicted with a wrestling match in Tokyo that would pay him $5 million. Jenkins auditioned other tall men, including [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], [[Lou Ferrigno]] and [[Carel Struycken]], but these did not pan out. Near the end of casting, the World Wrestling Federation told Jenkins that Andre's match in Tokyo had been cancelled, clearing him to play the role of Fezzik.<ref name=\"vice casting\"/>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Cliffs of Moher, looking north.jpg|thumb|The [[establishing shot]] of the Cliffs of Insanity is the [[Cliffs of Moher]] in [[County Clare]], Ireland.]]\nThe film was shot in various locations in [[Great Britain]] and [[Ireland]] in late 1986:<ref>{{cite web|author=Kent Film Office|url=http://kentfilmoffice.co.uk/1987/03/the-princess-bride-1987/|title=Kent Film Office The Princess Bride Film Focus}}</ref>\n* [[Carl Wark]], Sheffield, England\n* [[Burnham Beeches]], Buckinghamshire, England\n* [[River Lathkill|Lathkill Dale]] where it meets Cales Dale (the 'Battle of wits' scene)\n* [[Cave Dale]], [[Castleton, Derbyshire|Castleton]], Derbyshire, England\n* Bradley Rocks and [[Robin Hood's Stride]], Birchover, Derbyshire, England\n* [[Cliffs of Moher]], [[County Clare]], Ireland (for the Cliffs of Insanity)\n* [[Haddon Hall]], [[Bakewell]], Derbyshire, England\n* [[Penshurst Place]], [[Kent]], England\n\nThe framing story scenes, the last to be filmed, were recorded at [[Shepperton Studios]] in [[Surrey]].<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/>\n\nReiner rented a house in England near these sites and frequently invited the cast over for meals and light-hearted get-togethers. Many cast members believed this helped to create a sense of \"family\" that helped to improve their performances for the film.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/><ref name=\"ew 30th\">{{cite web | url = https://ew.com/movies/2017/10/03/princess-bride-cary-elwes-30th-anniversary/ | title = Cary Elwes talks sword fights, Andr\u00e9 the Giant, and The Princess Bride | first = Devan | last = Coggan | date = October 3, 2017 | accessdate = December 29, 2017 | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171230114715/http://ew.com/movies/2017/10/03/princess-bride-cary-elwes-30th-anniversary/ | archive-date = December 30, 2017 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nCary Elwes and Mandy Patinkin learned to [[Fencing|fence]] (both left- and right-handed) for the film, and performed these scenes themselves, outside of the two somersaults, which were performed by stunt doubles.<ref>Reiner, Rob. ''The Princess Bride''. DVD audio commentary. Directed by Rob Reiner. 1987; Santa Monica, CA: MGM Home Entertainment, 2001. ''(see Ch. 06, time 17:45)''</ref> They were trained by fencing instructors [[Bob Anderson (fencer)|Bob Anderson]] and Peter Diamond, both of whom had also worked on training the actors in the original ''[[Star Wars]]'' trilogy. Elwes and Patinkin spent about three weeks prior to filming learning to fence, and spent most of their off-camera free time practicing.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/><ref name=\"ew 30th\"/> Anderson encouraged the two to learn the other's choreography for the fight to help them anticipate the movements and avoid an accident.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/> They also watched as many sword fights from previous films to see how they could improve on those.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/>\n\nPopular professional wrestler Andr\u00e9 the Giant had undergone major back surgery prior to filming and, despite his great size and strength, could not support the weight of Elwes during their fight scene or Wright for a scene at the end of the film. For the wrestling scene, when Elwes hangs on Andr\u00e9's back, he was actually walking on a series of ramps below the camera during close-ups. For the wide shots, a stunt double took the place of Andr\u00e9.<ref>Reiner, Rob. ''The Princess Bride''. DVD audio commentary. Directed by Rob Reiner. 1987; Santa Monica, CA: MGM Home Entertainment, 2001. ''(see Ch. 08, time 25:40)''</ref> When he was apparently carrying Wright, she was actually suspended by cables.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.contactmusic.com/robin-wright/news/wright-giant-was-in-so-much-pain-on-the-princess-bride-set_1134854 | title = Wright: 'Giant Was In So Much Pain On The Princess Bride Set' | date = March 10, 2010 | website = [[Contactmusic.com]] | access-date = October 20, 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160221030137/http://www.contactmusic.com/robin-wright/news/wright-giant-was-in-so-much-pain-on-the-princess-bride-set_1134854 | archive-date = February 21, 2016 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBilly Crystal and Carol Kane spent time before traveling to England to work out the backstory between Miracle Max and his wife, and develop a rapport for their characters. Once on set, Reiner allowed the pair to improvise some of their lines.<ref name=\"variety 30th\"/>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|The Princess Bride (soundtrack)}}\nThe original soundtrack album was composed by [[Mark Knopfler]] of [[Dire Straits]], and released by [[Warner Bros. Records]] in the United States and [[Vertigo Records]] internationally in November 1987. The album contains the song \"Storybook Love\", performed by [[Willy DeVille]] and produced by Mark Knopfler. It was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] at the [[60th Academy Awards]].<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|title=The Princess Bride|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-princess-bride-original-soundtrack-r84523|website=Allmusic|accessdate=November 23, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102074244/http://allmusic.com/album/the-princess-bride-original-soundtrack-r84523|archive-date=November 2, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn his audio commentary of the film on the special edition DVD, director [[Rob Reiner]] said that only Knopfler could create a soundtrack to capture the film's quirky yet romantic nature. Reiner was an admirer of Knopfler's work but did not know him before working on the film. He sent the script to him hoping he would agree to score the film. Knopfler agreed on one condition: that somewhere in the film Reiner would include the {{USS|Coral Sea|CV-43}} baseball cap (which had been modified to say \"USS Ooral Sea OV-4B\") he wore as Marty DiBergi in ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]''. Reiner was unable to produce the original cap, but did include a similar cap in the grandson's room. Knopfler later said he was joking.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nThe film was initially a modest success,<ref>{{cite journal | title= 'The Princess Bride' Turns 20 | journal = [[The Palm Beach Post]] | last = Gray Streeter |first = Leslie | date = December 9, 2007 | quote = [w]as a modest hit[...] }}</ref> grossing $30.8 million at the United States and Canada box office,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=princessbride.htm |title= The Princess Bride (1987 |work= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate= September 27, 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181104204409/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=princessbride.htm |archive-date= November 4, 2018 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref> on a $16 million production budget.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reiner's 'Princess' is charming|journal=[[USA Today]]|last=Clark|first=Mike|date=September 25, 1987|quote=Despite a $16 million budget, [...]}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''The Princess Bride'' received critical acclaim. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a 97% \"Certified Fresh\" rating, based on 74 reviews, with an average rating of 8.34/10. The site's consensus states: \"A delightfully postmodern fairy tale, ''The Princess Bride'' is a deft, intelligent mix of swashbuckling, romance, and comedy that takes an age-old damsel-in-distress story and makes it fresh.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = The Princess Bride (1987) | url = https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/princess_bride/ | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Flixster]] | accessdate =March 28, 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130830074446/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/princess_bride/ | archive-date = August 30, 2013 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds a score of 77 out of 100, based on 20 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = The Princess Bride | url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-princess-bride | publisher = [[CBS]] | work = [[Metacritic]] | access-date = November 14, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121025113832/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-princess-bride | archive-date = October 25, 2012 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all}}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade \"A+\" on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |url-status= live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= December 20, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[Gene Siskel]] and [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film a \"two thumbs up\" rating on [[At the Movies (1986 TV program)|their television program]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/atm/reviews.html?sec=1&subsec=1737 |title=''At the Movies with Gene Siskel and Roger Ebert'' review |publisher=Bventertainment.go.com |accessdate=August 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070401175155/http://www.nypost.com/seven/02162007/entertainment/theater/bride_not_to_be_theater_michael_riedel.htm |archive-date= April 1, 2007 }}</ref> Ebert also wrote a very favorable print review in his column for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web | author = Roger Ebert | authorlink = Roger Ebert | url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19871009/REVIEWS/710090301/1023 | title = The Princess Bride | work = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date = October 9, 1987 | access-date = December 5, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121012155114/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F19871009%2FREVIEWS%2F710090301%2F1023 | archive-date = October 12, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Richard Corliss]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' said the film was fun for the whole family,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,965565,00.html | title = Errol Flynn Meets Gunga Din THE PRINCESS BRIDE | author = Richard Corliss | work = Time | date = September 21, 1987 | access-date = June 28, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930093032/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,965565,00.html | archive-date = September 30, 2007 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and later, ''Time'' listed the film as one of the \"Best of '87\".<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,966369,00.html | title = Best of '87 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012153630/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,966369,00.html |archive-date=October 12, 2007 | magazine = Time | date = January 4, 1988 }}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the cast and the sweetness of the film.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B0DE2D8133DF936A1575AC0A961948260 | title = New York Times review | author = Janet Maslin | date = September 25, 1987 | author-link = Janet Maslin | newspaper = The New York Times }}</ref>\n\n===Legacy===\n''The Princess Bride'' was not a major box-office success, but it became a cult classic after its release to the home video market. The film is widely regarded as eminently quotable.<ref name=\"our-time\">{{cite web |last=Clarke |first=Suzan | url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2011/10/princess-bride-reunion-thanks-to-entertainment-weekly-magazine/ | title= 'Princess Bride' Reunion, Thanks to Entertainment Weekly Magazine |publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=October 7, 2011 | accessdate=March 9, 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008023923/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2011/10/princess-bride-reunion-thanks-to-entertainment-weekly-magazine/ |archivedate=October 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"wizard2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/princess-bride-the|title=Reelviews Movie Reviews: The Princess Bride|date=January 4, 2002|accessdate=October 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209061003/http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/princess-bride-the|archive-date=December 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Elwes noted in 2017, on the film's 30th anniversary, that fans still frequently come up to him and quote lines from the movie. According to him Wallace Shawn had it \"worse\", in that any time Wallace made a small error like dropping his keys, people would shout \"Inconceivable!\" to him.<ref name=\"ew 30th\"/>\n\nIn 2000, readers of ''[[Total Film]]'' magazine voted ''The Princess Bride'' the 38th greatest comedy film of all time. In 2006, William Goldman's screenplay was selected by the [[Writers Guild of America]] as the 84th best screenplay of all time; it earned the same ranking in the Guild's 2013 update.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 | last= Savage | first = Sophia |date= February 27, 2013  |title= WGA Lists Greatest Screenplays, From 'Casablanca' and 'Godfather' to 'Memento' and 'Notorious' |publisher=Writers Guild of America, West |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130306065813/http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |archive-date=March 6, 2013}}</ref> The film was selected number 88 on The [[American Film Institute]]'s (AFI) \"[[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Passions]]\" listing the 100 greatest film love stories of all time. [[BBC Radio 5 Live|BBC Radio 5]]'s resident film critic, [[Mark Kermode]], is a fan of the film, frequently considering it a model to which similar films aspire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://duncmcrae.blogspot.com/2015/06/20-princess-bride.html|title=20: The Princess Bride|website=This AKTing Lark|date=June 27, 2015|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, a bar themed after the film, named \"As You Wish,\" opened in Chicago. The menu features 16 themed cocktails.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/princess-bride-themed-as-you-wish-bar-chicago/index.html|title=Inconceivable! A Princess Bride-themed bar is popping up in Chicago|first=Kristen |last=Rogers|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n;[[American Film Institute]] lists\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs500.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs Nominees |access-date=June 30, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220152415/http://afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs500.pdf |archive-date=December 20, 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Passions]] \u2013 No. 88\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes]]:\n** \"Hello. My name is Inigo Montoya. You killed my father; prepare to die!\" \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/quotes400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes Nominees |access-date=June 30, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628043426/http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/quotes400.pdf |archive-date=June 28, 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n* [[AFI's 10 Top 10]] \u2013 Nominated Fantasy Film<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/drop/ballot.pdf|title=AFI.com Error|work=afi.com|access-date=June 30, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911161721/http://www.afi.com/drop/ballot.pdf|archive-date=September 11, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, director [[Jason Reitman]] staged a [[Live Read|live dramatic reading]] of ''The Princess Bride'' script at the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] (LACMA), with [[Paul Rudd]] as Westley; [[Mindy Kaling]] as Buttercup; [[Patton Oswalt]] as Vizzini; [[Kevin Pollak]] as Miracle Max; [[Goran Visnjic]] as Inigo Montoya; [[Cary Elwes]] (switching roles) as Humperdinck; director [[Rob Reiner]] as the grandfather; and [[Fred Savage]] reprising his role as the grandson.<ref>{{cite news |date= December 30, 2011 |last= Breznican |first= Anthony |title= 'The Princess Bride' Comes Alive! |url= https://ew.com/article/2011/12/30/princess-bride-comes-alive/ |newspaper= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120115050153/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20558503,00.html|archive-date= January 15, 2012|url-status= live|df= mdy-all|accessdate= August 25, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, director [[Ari Folman]] released a [[live-action animated film]] titled ''[[The Congress (2013 film)|The Congress]]'', which directly referenced ''The Princess Bride''. Folman's film starred [[Robin Wright]], playing both a live and animated version of herself, as a [[Motion capture|digitally cloned]] actress.<ref>{{cite web |author=Manohla Dargis |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/05/movies/robin-wright-stars-in-the-congress.html |title=Movie Review\u2014A Princess Bride in a Digital Forever |quote=...Ms. Wright [plays] a version of herself \u2014 a midcareer actress named Robin Wright who...starred in \u201cThe Princess Bride\"... |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 4, 2014 |accessdate=December 27, 2018 |author-link=Manohla Dargis }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Cary Elwes wrote ''As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales From the Making of The Princess Bride,'' a behind-the-scenes account of the film's production, co-written with Joe Layden.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/movie-won-internet|title=The Movie That Won the Internet |last=Kelly |first=Caitlin|date=October 25, 2014 |work=The New Yorker|access-date=December 29, 2017 |issn=0028-792X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230114837/https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/movie-won-internet|archive-date=December 30, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> To help Elwes recall the production, Lear sent him a bound copy of the filming's [[call sheet]]s.<ref name=\"ew 30th\"/> The book debuted at #3 on the New York Times Bestseller list.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2014/11/02/hardcover-nonfiction/|title=New York Times Bestsellers List - Hardcover Nonfiction|access-date=October 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028114038/https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2014/11/02/hardcover-nonfiction/|archive-date=October 28, 2017|url-status=live|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cary-elwes.org/about|title=Cary Elwes: Biography|access-date=October 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028094209/https://www.cary-elwes.org/about|archive-date=October 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to a foreword by director Rob Reiner and a limited edition poster, the book includes exclusive photos and interviews with the cast members from the 25th anniversary cast reunion, as well as unique stories and set secrets from the making of the film.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/As-You-Wish/Cary-Elwes/9781476764023|title=As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales from the Making of The Princess Bride|work=Simon & Schuster|access-date=October 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028093640/http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/As-You-Wish/Cary-Elwes/9781476764023|archive-date=October 28, 2017|url-status=live|isbn=9781476764023|date=October 14, 2014|last1=Elwes|first1=Cary|last2=Layden|first2=Joe}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Savage reprised his role as The Grandson in a PG-13 version of ''[[Deadpool 2]]'' entitled ''Once Upon a Deadpool'', with [[Deadpool]] taking the role of The Narrator and reading the ''Deadpool 2''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s story to him at bedtime and skipping over the more adult parts from the R-rated version.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://collider.com/new-deadpool-movie-release-date|title=New 'Deadpool' Movie Coming This December; Will Feature 'Princess Bride' Star Fred Savage|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=September 28, 2018|accessdate=September 30, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929004447/http://collider.com/new-deadpool-movie-release-date/|archivedate=September 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"OnceUpon\">{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2018/11/deadpool-ryan-reynolds-disney-pg13-marvel-1202495981/ | title = 'Once Upon A Deadpool': Ryan Reynolds (and Fred Savage) On Franchise's PG-13 Plunge | first = Geoff | last = Boucher | date = November 5, 2018 | accessdate = November 5, 2018 | work = [[Deadline Hollywood]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181105223630/https://deadline.com/2018/11/deadpool-ryan-reynolds-disney-pg13-marvel-1202495981/ | archive-date = November 5, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Post-theatrical release==\n{{Anchor|DVD|Video|Home video history}} \nIn North America, the film was released on VHS and [[Laserdisc]] in 1988 by [[Nelson Entertainment]], the latter being a \"bare bones\" release in [[Matte (filmmaking)|unmatted full screen]]. [[New Line Home Video]] reissued the VHS in 1994.<ref>''Billboard'' (May 21, 1994), page 55.)</ref> The film was also released on [[Video CD]] by [[Philips]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=|first= |title=CD Films/Music|magazine=[[Sega Saturn Magazine]] |issue=13|publisher=[[Emap International Limited]]|date=November 1996|page=97}}</ref>\n\n[[The Criterion Collection]] released a matted widescreen version, bare bones version on laserdisc in 1989, supplementing it with [[liner notes]]. In 1997 Criterion re-released the Laserdisc as a \"[[special edition]]\". This edition was [[widescreen]] and included an [[audio commentary]] by Rob Reiner, William Goldman, Andrew Scheinman, Billy Crystal and Peter Falk (this commentary would also later appear on the Criterion Blu-ray and DVD release); excerpts from the novel read by Rob Reiner; behind the scenes footage; a production scrapbook by unit photographer Clive Coote; design sketches by production designer Norman Garwood; and excerpts from the television series ''Morton and Hayes'', directed by Christopher Guest.\n\nBy 2000, [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]] had acquired the US home video rights to the film (as part of the \"pre-1996 Polygram film library\" package) and released the film on VHS and DVD. The DVD release featured the soundtrack remastered in [[Dolby Digital|Dolby Digital 5.1]] with the film in wide and full screen versions, and included the original US [[theatrical trailer]]. The next year MGM re-released the film in another widescreen \"special edition\", this time with two audio commentaries\u2014one by Rob Reiner, the other by William Goldman\u2014\"As You Wish\", \"Promotional\", and \"Making Of\" [[featurette]]s;{{Clarify|date=December 2010}} a \"Cary Elwes Video Diary\"; the US and UK theatrical trailers; four television spots; a photo gallery; and a collectible booklet.\n\nIn 2006, MGM and [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]] released a two-disc set with varying covers\u2014the \"Dread Pirate\" and \"Buttercup\" editions. Each featured their respective character, but had identical features: in addition to the features in the previous release were, the \"Dread Pirate Roberts: Greatest Legend of the Seven Seas\", \"Love is Like a Storybook Story\", and \"Miraculous Make Up\" featurettes, \"The Quotable Battle of Wits\" game, and Fezzik's \"Guide to Florin\" booklet.\n\nAnother year later, to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the film, MGM and [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] (whose corporate parent [[The Walt Disney Company]] holds all US rights to the film except for US home video rights) released the film with flippable cover art featuring the title displayed in an [[ambigram]]. This DVD did not include any of the bonus features from the older editions, but had new short featurettes and a new game. A [[Blu-ray|Blu-ray Disc]] was released on March 17, 2009, encoded in 5.1 [[DTS-HD Master Audio]]. Special features include two audio commentaries, the original theatrical trailer and eight featurettes.<ref>{{cite press release | url = http://www.hometheaterforum.com/htf/ht-software-high-definition/282196-mgm-press-release-princess-bride-blu-ray.html | title = MGM Press Release: The Princess Bride (Blu-ray)] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090210180244/http://www.hometheaterforum.com/htf/ht-software-high-definition/282196-mgm-press-release-princess-bride-blu-ray.html |archive-date= February 10, 2009 | via = Home Theater Forum }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the film was released for download in the [[iTunes Store]].<ref name=\"https://itunes.apple.com/ca/movie/the-princess-bride/id263952053\">{{cite web | url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/movie/the-princess-bride/id263952053 | title=Itunes \u2013 Princess Bride | accessdate=October 31, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130626173718/https://itunes.apple.com/ca/movie/the-princess-bride/id263952053 | archive-date=June 26, 2013 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe film is also available in [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]] where it is published by [[Lions Gate Entertainment]]. Its extras are the theatrical trailer and text filmographies.\n\nThe Criterion Collection released the film on Blu-ray and DVD on October 30, 2018. It included a new 4K digital transfer, the same audio commentary from the Criterion LaserDisc release, an edited 1987 audiobook reading of Goldman's novel by director Rob Reiner, new programs on William Goldman's screenplay and tapestry, a new interview with art director Richard Holland, an essay by author [[Sloane Crosley]], and a Blu-ray exclusive book highlighting four screenplays, as well as Goldman's introduction to the 1995 screenplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=23637|title=Criterion Announces October Titles|date=July 16, 2018|accessdate=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717070802/http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=23637|archive-date=July 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nIt was announced that composer [[Adam Guettel]] was working with William Goldman on a musical adaptation of ''The Princess Bride'' in 2006. The project was abandoned in February 2007 after Goldman reportedly demanded 75 percent of the author's share, even though Guettel was writing both the music and the lyrics.<ref>{{cite news|last=Riedel |first=Michael |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/02162007/entertainment/theater/bride_not_to_be_theater_michael_riedel.htm |title='Bride' Not to Be While Broderick Balks at 'Producers' |work=New York Post |date=February 16, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070225201851/http://www.nypost.com/seven/02162007/entertainment/theater/bride_not_to_be_theater_michael_riedel.htm |archive-date=February 25, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn late 2013, [[Disney Theatrical Productions]] announced that they would adapt a stage musical adaptation of ''The Princess Bride''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/172985/inconceivable-disney-stage-adaptation-of-the-princess-bride-in-the-works/|title=Inconceivable! Disney Stage Adaptation of The Princess Bride in the Works|website=Broadway.com|last=Champion|first=Lindsay|date=November 11, 2013|accessdate=February 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164557/https://www.broadway.com/buzz/172985/inconceivable-disney-stage-adaptation-of-the-princess-bride-in-the-works/|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A website was launched a couple of months later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Disney-Launches-THE-PRINCESS-BRIDE-Musical-Website-20140208|title=Disney Launches THE PRINCESS BRIDE Stage Musical Website|website=Broadway World|last=Cerasaro|first=Pat|date=February 8, 2014|accessdate=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819114918/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Disney-Launches-THE-PRINCESS-BRIDE-Musical-Website-20140208|archive-date=August 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, Rob Reiner said the project was still in development despite \"roadblocks\" and that [[Marc Shaiman]], [[Randy Newman]] and [[John Mayer]] had all been approached to write songs, but had turned them down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/rob-reiner-says-he-still-wants-to-see-a-princess-bride-stage-musical-com-326627|title=Rob Reiner Says He Still Wants to See a Princess Bride Stage Musical|website=Playbill|last1=Viagas|first1=Robert|last2=Hetrick|first2=Adam|date=May 11, 2016|accessdate=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301224957/http://www.playbill.com/article/rob-reiner-says-he-still-wants-to-see-a-princess-bride-stage-musical-com-326627|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, ''The Princess Bride'' was adapted by players of a [[virtual reality]] social game, ''[[Rec Room (video game)|Rec Room]]'', into what is likely to be the world's first full-length virtual reality stage production. The duration of the production was approximately 80 minutes, and ran for a total of four shows.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carson |first1=Erin |title=The Princess Bride performed live -- in a VR app |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-princess-bride-gets-the-vr-treatment/ |quote= The Orange Bucket Acting Troupe...pulled off what's likely the first full-length play performed in VR. |website=[[CNET]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite AV Media |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Seev70WSSk |title=Orange Bucket Acting Troupe presents: The Princess Bride - A Rec Room Tale |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=October 31, 2018 |accessdate=March 11, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, PlayRoom Entertainment released ''The Princess Bride: Storming the Castle'', a board game based on the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/35524|title=The Princess Bride: Storming the Castle - Board Game - BoardGameGeek|work=boardgamegeek.com|access-date=August 18, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081108052204/http://www.boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/35524|archive-date=November 8, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''The Princess Bride Game'' is a [[casual game|casual video game]] developed and published by New York game development studio Worldwide Biggies.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/6180318.html?sid=6180318&action=convert | title = Princess Bride game conceivable | author = Sinclair, Brenden | website = [[GameSpot]] | date = October 3, 2007 | accessdate = June 3, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110525174538/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6180318.html?sid=6180318&action=convert | archive-date = May 25, 2011 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.joystiq.com/2007/10/03/as-you-wish-princess-bride-game-in-development/ | title = As you wish, Princess Bride game in development | author = McElroy, Justin | publisher = [[Joystiq]] | date = October 3, 2007 | accessdate = June 5, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150128143748/http://www.joystiq.com/2007/10/03/as-you-wish-princess-bride-game-in-development/ | archive-date = January 28, 2015 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Potential remake==\nIn a September 2019 biographical article on Norman Lear in ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] [[CEO]] [[Tony Vinciquerra]], speaking of Lear's works and interest in remaking them, stated \"Very famous people whose names I won\u2019t use, but they want to redo ''The Princess Bride.''\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/norman-lear-sony-deal-emmys-one-day-at-a-time-1203337598/ | title = Norman Lear Won't Stop: TV Legend's Sony Deal Renewal Takes Him to Age 100 | first = Michael | last = Schneider | date = September 17, 2019 | accessdate = September 17, 2019 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] }}</ref> The reaction to this via social media was very negative, with fans of the film asserting that a remake would be a bad idea and, in reference to the film, \"inconceivable\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/18/entertainment/the-princess-bride-remake-trnd/index.html | title = 'The Princess Bride' remake idea has people crying inconceivable | first =  Marianne | last = Garvey |date = September 18, 2019 | accessdate = September 18, 2019 | publisher = [[CNN]] }}</ref> Elwes paraphrased the film saying \"There\u2019s a shortage of perfect movies in this world. It would be a pity to damage this one.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user= Cary_Elwes |author-link= Cary Elwes |number= 1174124906327330816 |date= September 17, 2019 |title= There\u2019s a shortage of perfect movies in this world. It would be a pity to damage this one. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190920130745/https:/twitter.com/Cary_Elwes/status/1174124906327330816 |archive-date= September 20, 2019 |url-status= live}}</ref> [[Jamie Lee Curtis]], Guest's wife, stated \"there is only ONE ''The Princess Bride'' and it's William Goldman and [Reiner]'s\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/18/the-princess-bride-remake-rumors-spur-social-media-outrage.html | title = 'The Princess Bride' remake rumors spur social media outrage | first =  Sarah | last = Whitten |date = September 18, 2019 | accessdate = September 18, 2019 | publisher = [[CNBC]] }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Notelist-lr}}\n\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* Goldman, William, ''Which Lie Did They Tell?'', Bloomsbury, 2000\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last=Elwes |first=Cary |author-link1=Cary Elwes |last2=Layden |first2=Joe |date=2014 |title=As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales from the Making of The Princess Bride |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nNW5BAAAQBAJ |location=New York |publisher=Touchstone |oclc=878812649 |isbn=9781476764023}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.princessbrideforever.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|0093779}}\n* {{Tcmdb title|87152}}\n* {{Amg title|39218}}\n* {{AFI film|57788}}\n* {{mojo title|princessbride}}\n* [https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/6005-the-princess-bride-let-me-sum-up ''The Princess Bride: Let Me Sum Up''] an essay by [[Sloane Crosley]] at the [[Criterion Collection]]\n\n{{Rob Reiner}}\n{{William Goldman}}\n{{Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation 1981\u20132002}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Fantasy Film 1973\u20131990}}\n{{TIFF People's Choice Award}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States|1980s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Princess Bride, The}}\n[[Category:The Princess Bride| ]]\n[[Category:1980s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:1980s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:1980s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:1980s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1980s satirical films]]\n[[Category:1987 films]]\n[[Category:1980s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:1987 soundtracks]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:American children's adventure films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about royalty]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about weddings]]\n[[Category:Films based on adventure novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on romance novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by William Goldman]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Rob Reiner]]\n[[Category:Films set in a fictional country]]\n[[Category:Films about giants]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation winning works]]\n[[Category:Pirate films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by William Goldman]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "work's name, replaced:Hollywood Reporter\u2192The Hollywood Reporter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Princess_Bride_(film)"}
